00:17:08.500 --> 00:17:14.109
So Danny, can you speak real
quick to what the process was.

00:17:14.109 --> 00:17:16.240
How did this ever
get from your mind

00:17:16.240 --> 00:17:18.369
onto the page in the
first place in '93,

00:17:18.369 --> 00:17:21.069
with the late, great Harold
Ramis, you co-wrote, and then

00:17:21.069 --> 00:17:25.490
now to on the Broadway stage?

00:17:25.490 --> 00:17:27.690
How did this whole
process start?

00:17:27.690 --> 00:17:30.166
DANNY RUBIN: Well, I was
looking for an idea for a move.

00:17:30.166 --> 00:17:31.050
I was a screenwriter.

00:17:31.050 --> 00:17:32.440
And I needed to write a movie.

00:17:32.440 --> 00:17:34.862
My agent said, you need
to write another one.

00:17:34.862 --> 00:17:35.362
I said OK.

00:17:35.362 --> 00:17:38.591
And I was just
brainstorming ideas.

00:17:38.591 --> 00:17:40.215
And that's how I came
up with that one.

00:17:40.215 --> 00:17:41.890
And I wrote the script.

00:17:41.890 --> 00:17:44.286
And I sent it out
into the ether.

00:17:44.286 --> 00:17:45.850
And Harold Ramis found it.

00:17:45.850 --> 00:17:48.370
That's how we wound up
working together on the film.

00:17:48.370 --> 00:17:49.400
SPEAKER: Wow.

00:17:49.400 --> 00:17:50.101
And then--

00:17:50.101 --> 00:17:51.351
DANNY RUBIN: You said quickly.

00:17:51.351 --> 00:17:53.806
I can tell [INAUDIBLE]
much longer.

00:17:53.806 --> 00:17:55.130
SPEAKER: No, that is great.

00:17:55.130 --> 00:17:59.650
And then, so fast forward
over almost 25 years later.

00:17:59.650 --> 00:18:02.816
First off, is anybody not
familiar with the story?

00:18:02.816 --> 00:18:03.940
Everybody here knows, good.

00:18:03.940 --> 00:18:05.890
All right, phew.

00:18:05.890 --> 00:18:08.410
All right, for anybody watching
online, pause right now,

00:18:08.410 --> 00:18:11.440
go watch the movie, come back,
listen to the soundtrack.

00:18:11.440 --> 00:18:16.850
All right, how did
it get to the stage?

00:18:16.850 --> 00:18:18.610
How did you make a
musical out of this?

00:18:18.610 --> 00:18:21.130
DANNY RUBIN: For years and
years, really very soon

00:18:21.130 --> 00:18:23.337
after the movie came
out, I was thinking, boy,

00:18:23.337 --> 00:18:24.670
this would make a great musical.

00:18:24.670 --> 00:18:26.650
And I'd like to do that.

00:18:26.650 --> 00:18:31.150
And so I spent many years taking
notes, meeting with people,

00:18:31.150 --> 00:18:31.754
having ideas.

00:18:31.754 --> 00:18:32.670
I wasn't in any hurry.

00:18:32.670 --> 00:18:34.290
I was just starting
to collect things.

00:18:34.290 --> 00:18:39.910
It finally reached critical
mass after about 15 years.

00:18:39.910 --> 00:18:43.000
And all through that
time I was getting calls

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:46.003
from people in the
theater world saying,

00:18:46.003 --> 00:18:47.336
hey, I just had this great idea.

00:18:47.336 --> 00:18:49.600
Wouldn't "Groundhog Day"
make a great musical?

00:18:49.600 --> 00:18:52.350
I said, yeah, let's
talk about it.

00:18:52.350 --> 00:18:56.890
And after years of doing that
and having never really hitting

00:18:56.890 --> 00:19:00.310
the right people at the
right moment, Matthew Warchus

00:19:00.310 --> 00:19:03.177
called me up and said, hey, do
you think "Groundhog Day" would

00:19:03.177 --> 00:19:04.010
make a good musical?

00:19:04.010 --> 00:19:06.020
I said, absolutely, great idea.

00:19:06.020 --> 00:19:08.080
And then introduced
me to Tim Minchin.

00:19:08.080 --> 00:19:09.864
And we were off and running.

00:19:09.864 --> 00:19:13.432
SPEAKER: So how did Tim then,
how did Tim get attached?

00:19:13.432 --> 00:19:14.890
DANNY RUBIN: Because
he and Matthew

00:19:14.890 --> 00:19:16.364
are attached at the hip.

00:19:16.364 --> 00:19:18.445
And when you get one,
you get the other.

00:19:18.445 --> 00:19:19.320
SPEAKER: Fair enough.

00:19:19.320 --> 00:19:21.732
And then for all of
you on stage now,

00:19:21.732 --> 00:19:23.440
it was originally
workshopped, of course,

00:19:23.440 --> 00:19:25.330
or not even workshopped
in one [INAUDIBLE]..

00:19:25.330 --> 00:19:28.960
It went up like full
production in London.

00:19:28.960 --> 00:19:32.017
Were any of you involved in
that production out there?

00:19:32.017 --> 00:19:32.600
ANDY KARL: Me.

00:19:32.600 --> 00:19:35.039
I went in as the American,
came out the American.

00:19:35.039 --> 00:19:36.705
SPEAKER: You didn't
change nationalities

00:19:36.705 --> 00:19:37.580
while you were there?

00:19:37.580 --> 00:19:40.060
ANDY KARL: No, no, no,
though London is lovely.

00:19:40.060 --> 00:19:43.330
And they really embraced
the musical there.

00:19:43.330 --> 00:19:46.140
It was very well-received there.

00:19:46.140 --> 00:19:48.020
So that was fun.

00:19:48.020 --> 00:19:52.150
And it was a
fantastic experience.

00:19:52.150 --> 00:19:53.634
We spent most of the time--

00:19:53.634 --> 00:19:54.800
I was there for five months.

00:19:54.800 --> 00:19:56.920
And most of that time
was actually figuring out

00:19:56.920 --> 00:19:59.590
how those five revolves work.

00:19:59.590 --> 00:20:03.160
Because what Matthew
Warchus is is

00:20:03.160 --> 00:20:06.880
sort of a mathematician who
can also give you emotions.

00:20:06.880 --> 00:20:09.950
So it's two things at
once that are happening.

00:20:09.950 --> 00:20:12.760
And the floor moves within
an inch of its life.

00:20:12.760 --> 00:20:13.810
And it's very important.

00:20:13.810 --> 00:20:16.030
It actually, it
affects our story.

00:20:16.030 --> 00:20:19.570
The way that it revolves
is kind of like a clock.

00:20:19.570 --> 00:20:21.940
So every day, rewind--

00:20:21.940 --> 00:20:22.780
SPEAKER: Symbolism.

00:20:22.780 --> 00:20:24.342
ANDY KARL: --every
day moves forward.

00:20:24.342 --> 00:20:26.050
And when the end of
the show, it changes.

00:20:26.050 --> 00:20:29.640
And then every revolve
revolves alone of itself.

00:20:29.640 --> 00:20:32.350
So it tells stories.

00:20:32.350 --> 00:20:34.090
And it makes it very cinematic.

00:20:34.090 --> 00:20:35.580
And it's a beautiful
show to watch.

00:20:35.580 --> 00:20:37.330
But that took a lot
of time to figure out,

00:20:37.330 --> 00:20:40.480
and also just making sure
that the scenes worked out

00:20:40.480 --> 00:20:41.330
the way they did.

00:20:41.330 --> 00:20:43.400
I think they discovered
a lot of things there.

00:20:43.400 --> 00:20:44.830
And then we came here.

00:20:44.830 --> 00:20:49.330
And with this incredible cast,
refined it even more to really

00:20:49.330 --> 00:20:52.090
sort of eliminate
the things you don't

00:20:52.090 --> 00:20:54.532
need with a show, which
is what you find out

00:20:54.532 --> 00:20:55.490
as you're doing a show.

00:20:55.490 --> 00:20:56.300
It's like, you know what?

00:20:56.300 --> 00:20:57.008
We don't need it.

00:20:57.008 --> 00:20:59.410
We're telling that with
movement or whatever.

00:20:59.410 --> 00:21:00.850
But the show moves fast.

00:21:00.850 --> 00:21:03.040
But it's also tells
an incredible journey

00:21:03.040 --> 00:21:04.760
within those 2 and 1/2 hours.

00:21:04.760 --> 00:21:06.343
SPEAKER: And then
for the rest of you,

00:21:06.343 --> 00:21:09.550
