because it became a different
character in some ways,

00:34:03.540 --> 00:34:08.429
when Tim and Danny
expanded her inner life.

00:34:08.429 --> 00:34:10.384
ANDY KARL: I haven't
seen Bill at the show.

00:34:10.384 --> 00:34:11.550
SPEAKER: I was going to ask.

00:34:11.550 --> 00:34:14.190
ANDY KARL: If he's Googling
right now, please come see.

00:34:14.190 --> 00:34:15.209
Come on, man.

00:34:15.209 --> 00:34:17.310
BARRETT DOSS: I sort of
hope he's like snuck in,

00:34:17.310 --> 00:34:20.250
and like he's going to end up
on stage one day, accidentally,

00:34:20.250 --> 00:34:23.144
like wearing the Groundhog
suit or something.

00:34:23.144 --> 00:34:24.060
He just like walks in.

00:34:24.060 --> 00:34:25.630
ANDY KARL: It's
gonna be fantastic.

00:34:25.630 --> 00:34:29.639
But that's, but also I
think he and the writers

00:34:29.639 --> 00:34:31.530
of the original movie
brought the funny.

00:34:31.530 --> 00:34:34.409
And the funny is
still in this show.

00:34:34.409 --> 00:34:37.062
I find it goes even
funnier because what you're

00:34:37.062 --> 00:34:39.270
watching on stage, how are
they going to make the day

00:34:39.270 --> 00:34:41.340
repeat without it being corny?

00:34:41.340 --> 00:34:43.170
It's all about, it's slick.

00:34:43.170 --> 00:34:44.400
And it's funny.

00:34:44.400 --> 00:34:47.610
And it's intros to new
days, which become--

00:34:47.610 --> 00:34:49.300
which is interesting.

00:34:49.300 --> 00:34:52.215
The audience is ahead and
knows what's happening.

00:34:52.215 --> 00:34:53.340
The day is going to repeat.

00:34:53.340 --> 00:34:55.770
But they're never
ahead of how we're

00:34:55.770 --> 00:34:58.210
going to do it, which
I find beautiful.

00:34:58.210 --> 00:35:00.870
Like I don't know how you
guys wrote that and made

00:35:00.870 --> 00:35:01.940
that happen.

00:35:01.940 --> 00:35:06.510
But it's knock 'em down,
like really funny first act.

00:35:06.510 --> 00:35:10.260
Second act goes a little dark,
because he's living that day

00:35:10.260 --> 00:35:11.400
over and over again.

00:35:11.400 --> 00:35:12.570
Where do you go from there?

00:35:12.570 --> 00:35:14.850
They've explored
that territory of how

00:35:14.850 --> 00:35:19.372
someone deals with reliving this
same day over and over again.

00:35:19.372 --> 00:35:21.080
Because it can be fun
for a little while.

00:35:21.080 --> 00:35:22.831
And then it gets to be a drag.

00:35:22.831 --> 00:35:23.830
And then what do you do?

00:35:23.830 --> 00:35:25.840
And then how is he
going to snap out of it?

00:35:25.840 --> 00:35:28.870
And luckily Rita is
there to give him

00:35:28.870 --> 00:35:31.480
another way to look at things.

00:35:31.480 --> 00:35:33.400
SPEAKER: Talking
about that a second,

00:35:33.400 --> 00:35:36.880
I wanted to ask all
of you what you all

00:35:36.880 --> 00:35:39.310
thought the actual
interpretation of the show,

00:35:39.310 --> 00:35:40.720
what it all represents?

00:35:40.720 --> 00:35:41.650
I was reading online.

00:35:41.650 --> 00:35:44.590
There were so many,
again, theories.

00:35:44.590 --> 00:35:46.930
And hopefully Danny
will, if he's allowed to,

00:35:46.930 --> 00:35:49.150
depending on what he's
signed, could tell us

00:35:49.150 --> 00:35:50.560
what it actually means.

00:35:50.560 --> 00:35:52.390
My, I mean, is it purgatory?

00:35:52.390 --> 00:35:53.590
Are you Jesus?

00:35:53.590 --> 00:35:55.365
Is this something
happening with--

00:35:55.365 --> 00:35:56.990
REBECCA FAULKENBERRY:
Jesus, that's it.

00:35:56.990 --> 00:35:58.270
SPEAKER: Yeah, just Jesus.

00:35:58.270 --> 00:35:59.950
REBECCA FAULKENBERRY:
You guessed it.

00:35:59.950 --> 00:36:01.360
SPEAKER: Like what's going on?

00:36:01.360 --> 00:36:03.252
Anybody, tell me what you think?

00:36:03.252 --> 00:36:04.885
ANDY KARL: I want
to hear that guy.

00:36:04.885 --> 00:36:05.510
SPEAKER: Danny?

00:36:05.510 --> 00:36:08.498
DANNY RUBIN: [LAUGHTER]
Yeah, the groundhog is Jesus.

00:36:11.990 --> 00:36:14.690
I think that the story
speaks for itself.

00:36:14.690 --> 00:36:19.210
In a way, I don't have to
explain any of the themes,

00:36:19.210 --> 00:36:22.410
because everybody comes to
the show with themselves.

00:36:22.410 --> 00:36:24.477
And it connects in some way.

00:36:24.477 --> 00:36:26.185
Everybody has a
different interpretation.

00:36:26.185 --> 00:36:29.550
And every single one seems
stronger than the last.

00:36:29.550 --> 00:36:32.310
I have no reason to
define it differently.

00:36:32.310 --> 00:36:33.630
It's a very big--

00:36:33.630 --> 00:36:36.750
it's just the story of this
person going through this epic

00:36:36.750 --> 00:36:38.090
life all in one day.

00:36:38.090 --> 00:36:41.256
And I think we all relate to
it within our own language,

00:36:41.256 --> 00:36:43.380
so whether it's from a
philosophical point of view,

00:36:43.380 --> 00:36:47.100
or a religious point of view,
or just a humanistic view.

00:36:47.100 --> 00:36:49.929
It is something
that we all share.

00:36:49.929 --> 00:36:50.720
SPEAKER: Well said.

00:36:50.720 --> 00:36:51.220
All right.

00:36:51.220 --> 00:36:53.550
That was a vague an
answer as I expected, yes.

00:36:53.550 --> 00:36:55.542
AUDIENCE: [LAUGHTER]

00:36:55.542 --> 00:36:56.957
DANNY RUBIN: I'm a pro, man.

00:36:56.957 --> 00:36:58.790
SPEAKER: Actually that
wasn't the first time

00:36:58.790 --> 00:36:59.930
you've been asked.

00:36:59.930 --> 00:37:02.000
We have a mic in the
middle of the room here.

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:03.650
If anybody has
questions for Danny

00:37:03.650 --> 00:37:06.140
or the cast here on
stage, please line up

00:37:06.140 --> 00:37:09.537
and ask those questions, or
get ready to ask questions.

00:37:09.537 --> 00:37:11.120
For-- you were going
to say something?

00:37:11.120 --> 00:37:11.995
ANDY KARL: Or a song.

00:37:11.995 --> 00:37:15.290
SPEAKER: Or a song, if
you want to sing, yeah.

00:37:15.290 --> 00:37:18.740
Give your track to the
techs in the back and yeah.

00:37:18.740 --> 00:37:19.751
I want to talk quickly--

00:37:19.751 --> 00:37:21.500
something, Barrett,
you said a second ago,

00:37:21.500 --> 00:37:24.120
about that women have a
voice in this, more than,

00:37:24.120 --> 00:37:25.070
more so in the movie.

00:37:25.070 --> 00:37:29.570
And that touches
on, like the first--

00:37:29.570 --> 00:37:31.436
I talked to a friend
before I saw the show.

00:37:31.436 --> 00:37:32.060
And she saw it.

00:37:32.060 --> 00:37:33.980
She was like, I don't
know if I really like it

00:37:33.980 --> 00:37:35.900
because it was so sexist.

00:37:35.900 --> 00:37:40.700
And then I talked to her
again after I saw it.

00:37:40.700 --> 00:37:42.900
And she said, you know, the
more I thought about it,

00:37:42.900 --> 00:37:45.580
the more like Phil, he
just redeems himself.

00:37:45.580 --> 00:37:48.140
You go from one
extreme to the other.

00:37:48.140 --> 00:37:50.570
And then on top of
all of that, there's

00:37:50.570 --> 00:37:54.200
this new character of Nancy
that didn't exist in the movie.

00:37:54.200 --> 00:37:57.780
Like, I guess, Danny, what
was the point of putting,

00:37:57.780 --> 00:38:01.220
why did you put Nancy
into this version?

00:38:01.220 --> 00:38:03.880
DANNY RUBIN: Well, Nancy
was in the movie, of course.

00:38:03.880 --> 00:38:10.490
We just expanded her, giving
her a voice, a point of view.

00:38:10.490 --> 00:38:14.270
I think we were trying
to get the audience

00:38:14.270 --> 00:38:16.770
to go on Phil's journey.

00:38:16.770 --> 00:38:21.385
And by-- we think we've
taken the measure of how

00:38:21.385 --> 00:38:22.860
Phil is going to
progress, and how

00:38:22.860 --> 00:38:24.550
the show is going to progress.

00:38:24.550 --> 00:38:28.520
And right at the beginning
of Act II we do a full stop

00:38:28.520 --> 00:38:30.200
and say, oh, you know what?

00:38:30.200 --> 00:38:31.650
You were just like Phil.

00:38:31.650 --> 00:38:33.560
You were assuming you
understood everything

00:38:33.560 --> 00:38:35.020
about this character.

00:38:35.020 --> 00:38:37.070
And you knew what she was about.

00:38:37.070 --> 00:38:39.165
And we're going to
show you that you

00:38:39.165 --> 00:38:41.810
can look at her as a
real person now, not just

00:38:41.810 --> 00:38:43.718
as a prop in Phil's story.

00:38:43.718 --> 00:38:45.485
And we get that from her.

00:38:45.485 --> 00:38:46.985
And you hear the
whole audience sort

00:38:46.985 --> 00:38:50.475
of feeling this collective
guilt, like yeah,

00:38:50.475 --> 00:38:51.820
I kind of ignored her.

00:38:51.820 --> 00:38:53.800
I forgot she was a person too.

00:38:53.800 --> 00:38:57.695
And it has a big emotional
impact in driving you

00:38:57.695 --> 00:38:58.528
into the second act.

00:38:58.528 --> 00:39:00.020
That's what that was about.

00:39:00.020 --> 00:39:00.920
REBECCA FAULKENBERRY:
There's this wonderful--

00:39:00.920 --> 00:39:03.980
just going with that, with the
audience kind of feeling this

00:39:03.980 --> 00:39:05.409
guilt of like, oh, I didn't--

00:39:05.409 --> 00:39:06.200
why is she singing?

00:39:06.200 --> 00:39:06.740
And we don't need her.

00:39:06.740 --> 00:39:08.720
And then you hear the point
of the song, of saying,

00:39:08.720 --> 00:39:10.400
you didn't look at me as
anything more than this.

00:39:10.400 --> 00:39:12.440
And they go, oh, well,
that's what I was thinking.

00:39:12.440 --> 00:39:14.160
That's the whole point
of why the song is there.

00:39:14.160 --> 00:39:16.110
But there's this beautiful
like, douche trap,

00:39:16.110 --> 00:39:19.160
I like to call it, in the first,
like, two lines of the songs,

00:39:19.160 --> 00:39:21.870
when occasionally, on a
rowdy audience, because like,

00:39:21.870 --> 00:39:23.870
well, here I am again,
the pretty but naive one,

00:39:23.870 --> 00:39:25.560
the perky-breasted,
giggly, one night stand.

00:39:25.560 --> 00:39:26.210
[? SPEAKER: ?] Yeah!

00:39:26.210 --> 00:39:27.320
REBECCA FAULKENBERRY:
I guess the word breast

00:39:27.320 --> 00:39:29.130
is very exciting for people.

00:39:29.130 --> 00:39:31.020
And so sometimes a
dude or something

00:39:31.020 --> 00:39:33.132
will be like, yeah, or woohoo!

00:39:33.132 --> 00:39:35.034
I'm like, cool,
just wait a second.

00:39:35.034 --> 00:39:36.450
You're going to
feel, you're going

00:39:36.450 --> 00:39:39.890
to feel really bad about that.

00:39:39.890 --> 00:39:42.960
SPEAKER: And so it's, the song
is called, "Playing Nancy."

00:39:42.960 --> 00:39:44.120
You're singing it as Nancy.

00:39:44.120 --> 00:39:46.400
But Rebecca is singing.

00:39:46.400 --> 00:39:49.604
Who is, who, is
mouthing these words?

00:39:49.604 --> 00:39:51.020
Where are these
words coming from?

00:39:51.020 --> 00:39:51.890
REBECCA FAULKENBERRY:
You know that when

00:39:51.890 --> 00:39:53.630
you were asking about how
many days are in the show,

00:39:53.630 --> 00:39:56.052
and Danny was saying it's
really open to interpretation.

00:39:56.052 --> 00:39:58.010
I think this show is so
open to interpretation.

00:39:58.010 --> 00:39:59.843
I think that's what's
so great about theater

00:39:59.843 --> 00:40:02.060
and art in general, is that
like you'll read a book,

00:40:02.060 --> 00:40:03.860
or read something, and you
go, this is what it was about.

00:40:03.860 --> 00:40:05.000
And the metaphors,
and someone else

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:06.705
will get something
completely different.

00:40:06.705 --> 00:40:09.080
And I had someone at stage
door the other day, he's like,

00:40:09.080 --> 00:40:10.550
see what you were doing there.

00:40:10.550 --> 00:40:11.170
I got it.

00:40:11.170 --> 00:40:13.030
I was like, did you?

00:40:13.030 --> 00:40:14.330
What was I doing?

00:40:14.330 --> 00:40:17.450
He's like, because,
you're Nancy singing it.

00:40:17.450 --> 00:40:18.500
But it's really Rebecca.

00:40:18.500 --> 00:40:19.490
You're singing it.

00:40:19.490 --> 00:40:22.190
And oddly enough, in
my performance of it,

00:40:22.190 --> 00:40:24.860
I have never done it
as myself, because just

00:40:24.860 --> 00:40:27.464
as an actor, that would
feel very bizarre for me.

00:40:27.464 --> 00:40:29.630
I mean, it's bizarre enough
to break the fourth wall

00:40:29.630 --> 00:40:31.910
and talk directly to
the audience in a show.

00:40:31.910 --> 00:40:33.500
But I can do that as Nancy.

00:40:33.500 --> 00:40:36.140
If I turned around as Nancy
and then was like, hey guys,

00:40:36.140 --> 00:40:36.650
what's up?

00:40:36.650 --> 00:40:38.191
It's like, Rebecca
Faulkenberry here.

00:40:38.191 --> 00:40:40.790
I'm going to tell you my
story, which is not my own.

00:40:40.790 --> 00:40:42.429
I mean, I can
certainly, very much

00:40:42.429 --> 00:40:43.970
relate to this song
in a lot of ways.

00:40:43.970 --> 00:40:45.230
But it's not my own words.

00:40:45.230 --> 00:40:46.170
It's not my own story.

00:40:46.170 --> 00:40:47.330
So I can't do it as myself.

00:40:47.330 --> 00:40:49.371
I have to still do
it as the character,

00:40:49.371 --> 00:40:51.620
even though I totally see
that interpretation of being

00:40:51.620 --> 00:40:54.140
able to do it as
the actor and how

00:40:54.140 --> 00:40:55.550
it could relate to an actor.

00:40:55.550 --> 00:40:57.740
But I've never
done it as myself.

00:40:57.740 --> 00:41:00.410
But a lot of people will,
yeah, a lot of people

00:41:00.410 --> 00:41:03.045
will see and be like,
you were doing yourself.

00:41:03.045 --> 00:41:06.870
I'm like, no, but I'm glad that
that meant something to you.

00:41:06.870 --> 00:41:09.300
RAY LEE: And how many
times do you like,

00:41:09.300 --> 00:41:10.740
people expect to
be a certain way,

00:41:10.740 --> 00:41:13.530
or expect you to be this person,
and you play along to it.

00:41:13.530 --> 00:41:14.890
You know what I mean?

00:41:14.890 --> 00:41:15.960
How many times do you
go home and just kind of

00:41:15.960 --> 00:41:16.800
want to be yourself?

00:41:16.800 --> 00:41:18.500
But you don't have the
people that you can really

00:41:18.500 --> 00:41:19.120
be that with.

00:41:19.120 --> 00:41:20.260
So I love that song.

00:41:20.260 --> 00:41:23.067
I think it calls out, I
don't know, just people.

00:41:23.067 --> 00:41:24.650
BARRETT DOSS: But
I'd also like to add

00:41:24.650 --> 00:41:27.350
that I think the female
characters in the show have

00:41:27.350 --> 00:41:32.180
what I find, personally,
often lacking

00:41:32.180 --> 00:41:33.770
in female roles in
musical theater--

00:41:33.770 --> 00:41:36.410
that there's an incredible
amount of self-awareness.

00:41:36.410 --> 00:41:38.180
So when she is sort
of breaking down

00:41:38.180 --> 00:41:42.350
her own experience
of her life, or Rita,

00:41:42.350 --> 00:41:44.960
I get to do that in
"One Day," primarily,

00:41:44.960 --> 00:41:48.890
and also in "If I had my
Time Again" in a lot of ways,

00:41:48.890 --> 00:41:51.950
it feels less about how people
are-- well, in your case,

00:41:51.950 --> 00:41:53.600
it's how people are
experiencing you,

00:41:53.600 --> 00:41:56.570
but how you get to react to that
and process that information.

00:41:56.570 --> 00:41:58.730
And for me, in "One
Day," it feels very much

00:41:58.730 --> 00:42:03.800
like I get to comment on
my experience of men--

00:42:03.800 --> 00:42:06.320
or of relationships,
rather, not even just men,

00:42:06.320 --> 00:42:09.290
but of relationships
as my character,

00:42:09.290 --> 00:42:12.530
as opposed to how they feel
about me, which I don't think

00:42:12.530 --> 00:42:13.770
gets to happen that often.

00:42:13.770 --> 00:42:18.500
So there's what feels
very real about it,

00:42:18.500 --> 00:42:21.230
and what I identify with, as
far as Rita and Nancy goes,

00:42:21.230 --> 00:42:25.250
is that we all have this
inner life as human beings.

00:42:25.250 --> 00:42:27.440
And sometimes it feels
good to just let that

00:42:27.440 --> 00:42:29.220
out and share that with people.

00:42:29.220 --> 00:42:31.760
And it often feels like,
in musical theater,

00:42:31.760 --> 00:42:36.090
women get flattened, become
very two-dimensional.

00:42:36.090 --> 00:42:37.761
SPEAKER: A question here.

00:42:37.761 --> 00:42:39.260
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
first, I want to say

00:42:39.260 --> 00:42:40.551
thank you very much for coming.

00:42:40.551 --> 00:42:41.280
I love the show.

00:42:41.280 --> 00:42:42.239
It's really great.

00:42:42.239 --> 00:42:43.660
[? BARRETT DOSS: ?] Thank you!

00:42:43.660 --> 00:42:46.394
AUDIENCE: My question, I guess
it's maybe for Andy, London

00:42:46.394 --> 00:42:48.560
versus New York, did you
find there were differences

00:42:48.560 --> 00:42:50.310
in terms of like what
the audience wanted,

00:42:50.310 --> 00:42:52.040
what the audience expects?

00:42:52.040 --> 00:42:54.440
ANDY KARL: The reaction
was actually very similar,

00:42:54.440 --> 00:42:55.760
which I found interesting.

00:42:55.760 --> 00:42:57.770
I was told that
audiences in London

00:42:57.770 --> 00:43:03.990
don't stand up at the end,
or they're very, very nice.

00:43:03.990 --> 00:43:06.730
But they went bananas for it,
which I was like, all right,

00:43:06.730 --> 00:43:07.550
man!

00:43:07.550 --> 00:43:10.490
International success!

00:43:10.490 --> 00:43:15.590
I think because it's
so, like Danny said,

00:43:15.590 --> 00:43:19.350
it tells such a human story
that everyone can relate to,

00:43:19.350 --> 00:43:21.630
it's like, it singles
out every single body,

00:43:21.630 --> 00:43:23.360
every single person in the show.

00:43:23.360 --> 00:43:26.570
And they see it for
how they interpret it.

00:43:26.570 --> 00:43:30.052
And it's so effective that way.

00:43:30.052 --> 00:43:32.260
And I think that's what's
so important about the show

00:43:32.260 --> 00:43:37.340
and how it makes London
very similar to here.

00:43:37.340 --> 00:43:42.140
There was no cross-continental
divide about have they

00:43:42.140 --> 00:43:43.660
seen the movie or not.

00:43:43.660 --> 00:43:46.190
And I see a lot of people here
who haven't seen the movie.

00:43:46.190 --> 00:43:47.523
And they come to the stage door.

00:43:47.523 --> 00:43:49.370
And they're just blown
away by the story.

00:43:49.370 --> 00:43:53.690
And I think it
works well, so far.

00:43:53.690 --> 00:43:54.920
I don't know about Australia.

00:43:54.920 --> 00:43:56.900
I don't know about Germany.

00:43:56.900 --> 00:43:59.108
But who knows, maybe
it'll work there.

00:43:59.108 --> 00:44:00.980
BARRETT DOSS: I think
Tim's from Australia.

00:44:00.980 --> 00:44:02.391
SPEAKER: Next question.

00:44:02.391 --> 00:44:04.890
AUDIENCE: I'd also like to say
thank you so much for coming.

00:44:04.890 --> 00:44:06.710
I love the show.

00:44:06.710 --> 00:44:10.130
My question is, my
sister's in ninth grade.

00:44:10.130 --> 00:44:14.150
And her dream is to be
on stage professionally.

00:44:14.150 --> 00:44:19.200
Do you have any advice for
someone in that position?

00:44:19.200 --> 00:44:23.110
BARRETT DOSS: I've said
this a few times recently.

00:44:23.110 --> 00:44:25.180
It's really, I don't
know if she's a singer,

00:44:25.180 --> 00:44:27.471
or if she's interested in
musical theater specifically,

00:44:27.471 --> 00:44:32.051
but when I've met younger people
at the stage door, I'm always--

00:44:32.051 --> 00:44:33.300
who are into musical theater--

00:44:33.300 --> 00:44:35.730
I always say, please
don't forget your acting.

00:44:35.730 --> 00:44:37.140
Do not forget your acting.

00:44:37.140 --> 00:44:38.880
It's like incredibly important.

00:44:38.880 --> 00:44:43.232
I think it's easy to
forget when you get a lot--

00:44:43.232 --> 00:44:44.940
this going to sound
really shady, but I'm

00:44:44.940 --> 00:44:45.940
going to say it anyway--

00:44:45.940 --> 00:44:48.900
a lot of like pop stars
who come in to [? show, ?]

00:44:48.900 --> 00:44:54.300
it like it's really easy to miss
out on telling real stories,

00:44:54.300 --> 00:45:00.330
and understanding how to
recreate basic human emotion,

00:45:00.330 --> 00:45:02.490
in place of riffing
and doing all of that,

00:45:02.490 --> 00:45:03.780
all those vocal gymnastics.

00:45:03.780 --> 00:45:05.440
But acting is so important.

00:45:05.440 --> 00:45:07.260
And that's something
that I would

00:45:07.260 --> 00:45:10.860
encourage her to keep in mind.

00:45:10.860 --> 00:45:12.390
SPEAKER: Anybody else?

00:45:12.390 --> 00:45:16.470
JORDAN GRUBB: I'd say
embrace what you do,

00:45:16.470 --> 00:45:19.740
what you think is
better than anybody.

00:45:19.740 --> 00:45:21.540
Because in this industry,
I feel like there

00:45:21.540 --> 00:45:23.370
has to be something
that makes you special.

00:45:23.370 --> 00:45:24.786
Because there's
so many people who

00:45:24.786 --> 00:45:26.527
can act, and sing, and dance.

00:45:26.527 --> 00:45:28.110
But there has to be
something that you

00:45:28.110 --> 00:45:30.510
do in particular that
you bring to the table

00:45:30.510 --> 00:45:31.620
that nobody else does.

00:45:31.620 --> 00:45:33.840
And I think in my first
few years of living here,

00:45:33.840 --> 00:45:36.040
I kind of had a
crisis of confidence,

00:45:36.040 --> 00:45:40.020
and a crisis of self, and tried
to be this person I wasn't.

00:45:40.020 --> 00:45:42.900
And the minute I started
embracing my individuality,

00:45:42.900 --> 00:45:45.720
and saw what I did that was
different than everybody

00:45:45.720 --> 00:45:48.630
else, that's when the
jobs started coming.

00:45:48.630 --> 00:45:51.930
Because I think the
authenticity, in our business,

00:45:51.930 --> 00:45:52.860
is important.

00:45:52.860 --> 00:45:53.944
And I think it stands out.

00:45:53.944 --> 00:45:55.609
RAY LEE: Like,
piggybacking off of that,

00:45:55.609 --> 00:45:56.880
don't let anyone box you in.

00:45:56.880 --> 00:45:58.140
If I had listened
to the people that

00:45:58.140 --> 00:46:00.610
wanted to box me to a type,
with the certain types of shows

00:46:00.610 --> 00:46:04.849
I could have done, I wouldn't
be on the stage right now.

00:46:04.849 --> 00:46:06.640
REBECCA FAULKENBERRY:
Yeah, going with all,

00:46:06.640 --> 00:46:07.940
I mean, it's a hard business.

00:46:07.940 --> 00:46:09.970
Everyone knows that.

00:46:09.970 --> 00:46:11.350
I remember when
I was auditioning

00:46:11.350 --> 00:46:12.309
for colleges and stuff.

00:46:12.309 --> 00:46:13.891
You go into every
room and they always

00:46:13.891 --> 00:46:16.270
say, if there's anything else
you love, anything else you

00:46:16.270 --> 00:46:17.620
can think of doing, go do that.

00:46:17.620 --> 00:46:19.300
I'm like, that is so uninspired.

00:46:19.300 --> 00:46:21.709
Why would you say that
to a group of artists?

00:46:21.709 --> 00:46:23.500
And it wasn't until I
got into the business

00:46:23.500 --> 00:46:25.180
I was like, oh, that's
why they say it.

00:46:25.180 --> 00:46:28.196
Because truly, it's a very
difficult thing to do.

00:46:28.196 --> 00:46:30.320
And I even when my sister
was starting, I was like,

00:46:30.320 --> 00:46:32.530
can you see yourself
auditioning, not booking

00:46:32.530 --> 00:46:35.260
one job, and waitressing
for at least two years

00:46:35.260 --> 00:46:36.880
and having nothing
out of college?

00:46:36.880 --> 00:46:39.540
Can you do that and still
enjoy that and think,

00:46:39.540 --> 00:46:42.220
but for the possibility that
after two years or maybe longer

00:46:42.220 --> 00:46:43.136
I could get something?

00:46:43.136 --> 00:46:45.070
Because people go,
yeah, I could do that.

00:46:45.070 --> 00:46:46.000
But that won't be me.

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:47.999
Because I'm going to book
something as soon as I

00:46:47.999 --> 00:46:48.520
audition.

00:46:48.520 --> 00:46:50.800
And you really have to go
through those scenarios.

00:46:50.800 --> 00:46:53.320
And if after you think of all
that stuff, you still love it

00:46:53.320 --> 00:46:55.510
and you can't see yourself
doing anything else,

00:46:55.510 --> 00:46:57.370
then you just figure
out who you are.

00:46:57.370 --> 00:47:00.160
You embrace what you do,
learning how to act, especially

00:47:00.160 --> 00:47:01.060
for musical theater.

00:47:01.060 --> 00:47:04.260
And you just have to like go.

00:47:04.260 --> 00:47:05.490
And yeah.

00:47:05.490 --> 00:47:06.382
SPEAKER: Very good.

00:47:06.382 --> 00:47:07.090
ANDY KARL: Do it.

00:47:07.090 --> 00:47:07.840
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:47:07.840 --> 00:47:08.631
SPEAKER: Thank you.

00:47:08.631 --> 00:47:11.920
Danny-- oh, one more question?

00:47:11.920 --> 00:47:12.609
Yes, sorry.

00:47:12.609 --> 00:47:13.150
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:47:13.150 --> 00:47:15.630
I saw the show a few weeks ago.

00:47:15.630 --> 00:47:16.780
It was really great.

00:47:16.780 --> 00:47:19.315
One of my favorite
sequences was the sequence

00:47:19.315 --> 00:47:21.940
at the beginning of Act II, when
you're trying to kill yourself

00:47:21.940 --> 00:47:23.023
a bunch of different ways.

00:47:23.023 --> 00:47:24.440
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:24.440 --> 00:47:26.470
If you see it, it's amazing.

00:47:26.470 --> 00:47:28.847
So I was just wondering if
you could reveal a little bit

00:47:28.847 --> 00:47:29.680
about how you do it.

00:47:29.680 --> 00:47:31.600
Because you climb
up a ladder, and you

00:47:31.600 --> 00:47:33.750
appeared downstage
like two seconds later.

00:47:33.750 --> 00:47:35.291
[? BARRETT DOSS: ?]
Reveal the magic?

00:47:35.291 --> 00:47:37.720
ANDY KARL: Yeah, can't
reveal the magic.

00:47:37.720 --> 00:47:43.570
But it is a great number that
took a long time to figure out.

00:47:43.570 --> 00:47:47.110
And it's funny because it's
like, one of the harder songs

00:47:47.110 --> 00:47:48.970
I do in this show,
but I'm constantly

00:47:48.970 --> 00:47:51.580
crawling, and
jumping out of bed,

00:47:51.580 --> 00:47:55.300
and I'm appearing on one
stage, and then appearing

00:47:55.300 --> 00:47:56.650
on another side of the stage.

00:47:56.650 --> 00:48:00.420
Because it's a day that
happens really quickly.

00:48:00.420 --> 00:48:02.920
And it happens every
time I kill myself.

00:48:02.920 --> 00:48:09.077
And then I wake up in bed
again, alive, to my sadness.

00:48:09.077 --> 00:48:09.910
It's just beautiful.

00:48:09.910 --> 00:48:14.050
And Paul Kieve, who is another
person we should talk about,

00:48:14.050 --> 00:48:19.450
he is our magician for
the show, illusionist.

00:48:19.450 --> 00:48:21.910
He figured out a
lot of stagecraft,

00:48:21.910 --> 00:48:23.560
and staged distraction.

00:48:23.560 --> 00:48:27.160
And it's fun.

00:48:27.160 --> 00:48:29.770
And you would think that a
suicide number is not funny.

00:48:29.770 --> 00:48:32.500
It actually is
pretty damn funny.

00:48:32.500 --> 00:48:35.160
And the song is called "Hope."

00:48:35.160 --> 00:48:39.100
So is that an
oxymoron, I believe?

00:48:39.100 --> 00:48:42.130
And that's Tim
Minchin's brain at work.

00:48:42.130 --> 00:48:45.040
And then the way they staged it,
Matthew Warchus, and how big it

00:48:45.040 --> 00:48:47.230
is, and horrible it is.

00:48:47.230 --> 00:48:49.630
And then you have to go--
that's what's really great

00:48:49.630 --> 00:48:51.160
about it is that,
going through that

00:48:51.160 --> 00:48:54.670
is really funny and horrible,
and then coming out of that,

00:48:54.670 --> 00:48:57.010
realizing that that's
not the answer.

00:48:57.010 --> 00:49:00.250
On to the next
day, what do I do?

00:49:00.250 --> 00:49:02.410
But I'm glad you
liked that number.

00:49:02.410 --> 00:49:04.576
RAY LEE: And that was one
of the first numbers, too,

00:49:04.576 --> 00:49:06.281
I think we learned it.

00:49:06.281 --> 00:49:07.780
And Andy was always
like, just wait.

00:49:07.780 --> 00:49:10.150
Like, wait, like this got
such a reaction in London.

00:49:10.150 --> 00:49:10.940
And we're like OK.

00:49:10.940 --> 00:49:12.010
And then once we
started performing,

00:49:12.010 --> 00:49:14.010
it was so cool to see the
audience kind of freak

00:49:14.010 --> 00:49:16.030
out and just kind
of cheer for it.

00:49:16.030 --> 00:49:18.339
So it's a fun one.

00:49:18.339 --> 00:49:19.130
SPEAKER: Thank you.

00:49:19.130 --> 00:49:20.370
Danny, what's next for you?

00:49:20.370 --> 00:49:21.544
What are you writing?

00:49:21.544 --> 00:49:22.710
DANNY RUBIN: Lots of things.

00:49:22.710 --> 00:49:24.544
I'm trying to do things that--

00:49:24.544 --> 00:49:27.001
I live here in Santa
Fe, New Mexico.

00:49:27.001 --> 00:49:28.880
And there's so many
talented people here.

00:49:28.880 --> 00:49:31.070
I'm working to
write things that I

00:49:31.070 --> 00:49:33.370
can do with people
in my own community,

00:49:33.370 --> 00:49:37.472
without needing to go to
New York or Los Angeles.

00:49:37.472 --> 00:49:40.370
Which I enjoy when it
happens, but I thought

00:49:40.370 --> 00:49:43.017
I'd spend a couple
years just trying

00:49:43.017 --> 00:49:44.184
to do things closer to home.

00:49:44.184 --> 00:49:46.183
SPEAKER: That's why we
invented Google Hangouts,

00:49:46.183 --> 00:49:48.270
so we could bring you in
to these types of events.

00:49:48.270 --> 00:49:49.745
Yeah, so for the
rest of you here.

00:49:49.745 --> 00:49:50.120
DANNY RUBIN: Well done.

00:49:50.120 --> 00:49:51.539
SPEAKER: Oh, thank
you, thank you.

00:49:51.539 --> 00:49:54.080
For the rest of you here, what
is the one thing-- we're just,

00:49:54.080 --> 00:49:55.538
real quickly, we're
short on time--

00:49:55.538 --> 00:49:57.170
what is the one
thing that you all

00:49:57.170 --> 00:49:58.970
hope audiences
take with them when

00:49:58.970 --> 00:50:00.350
they leave after every show?

00:50:03.320 --> 00:50:09.320
ANDY KARL: A really good time
and a head full of thoughts.

00:50:09.320 --> 00:50:12.410
That's my favorite thing, people
going home thinking about it.

00:50:12.410 --> 00:50:14.630
And not only were
they entertained,

00:50:14.630 --> 00:50:20.068
but they were asked to
examine their own life.

00:50:20.068 --> 00:50:22.372
BARRETT DOSS: Yeah, I mean, I--

00:50:22.372 --> 00:50:24.080
JORDAN GRUBB: I was
going to say, I mean,

00:50:24.080 --> 00:50:27.050
that they, if you look
around in this year's season,

00:50:27.050 --> 00:50:28.850
we're one of the, really
the only comedies,

00:50:28.850 --> 00:50:31.190
if not the only
comedy of the season.

00:50:31.190 --> 00:50:33.355
So, and I used to get upset
when I would see people

00:50:33.355 --> 00:50:33.980
after the show.

00:50:33.980 --> 00:50:35.577
And they'd be like, it's so fun.

00:50:35.577 --> 00:50:37.160
And I'd be like, no,
I want you to say

00:50:37.160 --> 00:50:39.530
it's like the best thing you've
ever seen in your whole life.

00:50:39.530 --> 00:50:40.280
But you know what?

00:50:40.280 --> 00:50:41.570
It is fun.

00:50:41.570 --> 00:50:43.921
Like, if you leave
there and you are happy,

00:50:43.921 --> 00:50:45.920
and you are feeling good,
I mean that's theater.

00:50:45.920 --> 00:50:47.540
That's why you go
to the theater.

00:50:47.540 --> 00:50:49.280
So if you're having
a fun time and you

00:50:49.280 --> 00:50:51.200
leave us feeling better
than when you came in,

00:50:51.200 --> 00:50:52.325
like, mission accomplished.

00:50:52.325 --> 00:50:54.741
REBECCA FAULKENBERRY: Yeah,
good theater should affect you

00:50:54.741 --> 00:50:56.570
in some way, whether
you go away and it's

00:50:56.570 --> 00:50:57.945
leaving you
pondering life stuff,

00:50:57.945 --> 00:50:59.444
or you go away and
you think, I just

00:50:59.444 --> 00:51:00.950
laughed for two
and a half hours,

00:51:00.950 --> 00:51:04.719
or that just made me cry because
it made me contemplate my life,

00:51:04.719 --> 00:51:07.260
and where I've gone, and am I
living each day to the fullest.

00:51:07.260 --> 00:51:09.136
If it affects you in
some way, and you're not

00:51:09.136 --> 00:51:10.926
sitting there bored
out of your mind, which

00:51:10.926 --> 00:51:12.680
I guarantee you will
not be at this show,

00:51:12.680 --> 00:51:13.828
then it's done its job.

00:51:13.828 --> 00:51:15.786
RAY LEE: And we do
diversity right on Broadway.

00:51:15.786 --> 00:51:16.950
REBECCA FAULKENBERRY:
Oh yeah, absolutely.

00:51:16.950 --> 00:51:18.860
RAY LEE: So I'm
very proud of that.

00:51:18.860 --> 00:51:20.514
We aren't all token characters.

00:51:20.514 --> 00:51:21.680
We are not token characters.

00:51:21.680 --> 00:51:22.770
We are people.

00:51:22.770 --> 00:51:25.820
And I always tell people,
come see what we're doing.

00:51:25.820 --> 00:51:26.960
BARRETT DOSS: Yeah it's--

00:51:26.960 --> 00:51:30.650
and just to piggyback on that,
I agree with what all of us

00:51:30.650 --> 00:51:32.266
have said so far.

00:51:32.266 --> 00:51:34.640
But I do think that our show,
something that really makes

00:51:34.640 --> 00:51:38.600
our show special is not
only gender diversity, age

00:51:38.600 --> 00:51:41.780
diversity, race diversity,
size diversity, we really

00:51:41.780 --> 00:51:43.160
have created--

00:51:43.160 --> 00:51:48.980
this cast is filled with some of
the most talented and hilarious

00:51:48.980 --> 00:51:50.350
actors I've ever worked with.

00:51:50.350 --> 00:51:53.150
And every single one of
my castmates I feel like

00:51:53.150 --> 00:51:55.850
could carry an entire
show on their own.

00:51:55.850 --> 00:51:59.394
But everyone gets this moment
to be a part of a group.

00:51:59.394 --> 00:52:01.310
And together we make
something really special.

00:52:01.310 --> 00:52:03.860
So I hope you will come
see it and enjoy it.

00:52:03.860 --> 00:52:05.130
SPEAKER: Wonderful, thank you.

00:52:05.130 --> 00:52:06.520
Danny, thank you for joining us.

00:52:06.520 --> 00:52:08.630
All of you, thank you.

00:52:08.630 --> 00:52:11.930
The August Wilson Theater,
245 West 52nd Street

00:52:11.930 --> 00:52:13.100
is where it's playing.

00:52:13.100 --> 00:52:15.170
Go visit them online,
groundhogdaymusical.com,

00:52:15.170 --> 00:52:20.425
Twitter and Instagram,
@groundhogdaybway.

00:52:20.425 --> 00:52:22.550
And then, if you don't
mind, could you close us out

00:52:22.550 --> 00:52:23.845
with one more number?

00:52:23.845 --> 00:52:25.428
ANDY KARL: Oh do we
have another song?

00:52:25.428 --> 00:52:27.520
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:52:27.520 --> 00:52:28.926
ANDY KARL: Did I give that away?

00:52:28.926 --> 00:52:30.717
REBECCA FAULKENBERRY:
Do we have the track?

00:52:30.717 --> 00:52:31.340
I don't know.

00:52:31.340 --> 00:52:32.610
SPEAKER: I just
happened to bring it.

00:52:32.610 --> 00:52:33.620
REBECCA FAULKENBERRY:
Did we sound check this?

00:52:33.620 --> 00:52:35.420
ANDY KARL: Did we do this?

00:52:35.420 --> 00:52:38.120
Yeah, talk about diversity and
then the six-foot-two white guy

00:52:38.120 --> 00:52:41.825
gets up here and starts to,
jeez, close out the show.

00:52:41.825 --> 00:52:44.841
BARRETT DOSS: We know what
the show is about, Andy.

00:52:44.841 --> 00:52:46.340
ANDY KARL: I think
that's actually--

00:52:46.340 --> 00:52:49.250
it's really interesting
to do that part of the,

00:52:49.250 --> 00:52:50.886
have that happen.

00:52:50.886 --> 00:52:52.760
There's people I wish
would come see the show

00:52:52.760 --> 00:52:55.910
and just get a little
clue into a moment

00:52:55.910 --> 00:53:00.590
like this, which is, this last
song is called "Seeing You."

00:53:00.590 --> 00:53:03.440
And Phil has had
his full journey.

00:53:03.440 --> 00:53:06.890
He's gone through
being a jerk, and being

00:53:06.890 --> 00:53:09.500
really horrible to
people because he doesn't

00:53:09.500 --> 00:53:10.660
want to be in this town.

00:53:10.660 --> 00:53:13.460
Then being stuck in this
town with all these people.

00:53:13.460 --> 00:53:14.630
And how terrible is that?

00:53:14.630 --> 00:53:16.100
And then taking
advantage of that

00:53:16.100 --> 00:53:20.990
by being with someone like
Nancy for night after night.

00:53:20.990 --> 00:53:22.970
And then realizing
that's not the answer.

00:53:22.970 --> 00:53:24.410
There's got to be something new.

00:53:24.410 --> 00:53:27.080
And then going to
that dark place

00:53:27.080 --> 00:53:29.150
and just wanting to end it all.

00:53:29.150 --> 00:53:31.340
And he can't end it.

00:53:31.340 --> 00:53:33.650
Then he starts then,
then he actually

00:53:33.650 --> 00:53:36.330
has Rita to give them a
clue into saying, well,

00:53:36.330 --> 00:53:38.660
actually maybe
you're the lucky one.

00:53:38.660 --> 00:53:41.960
You get to live
something new every day.

00:53:41.960 --> 00:53:43.940
It's everybody
else that's stuck.

00:53:43.940 --> 00:53:46.370
And that's sparked
something in his brain.

00:53:46.370 --> 00:53:50.600
Then he becomes altruistic,
and helps people in the town.

00:53:50.600 --> 00:53:55.310
And through all this that his
accumulated through this show,

00:53:55.310 --> 00:53:58.580
he realizes that everybody
has become a part of his life

00:53:58.580 --> 00:54:00.590
and made him a better person.

00:54:00.590 --> 00:54:04.580
And he's able to see that
every day, in some nuance,

00:54:04.580 --> 00:54:06.620
in everybody.

00:54:06.620 --> 00:54:08.840
And it's beautiful.

00:54:08.840 --> 00:54:11.424
And this last song is called
"Seeing You," by Tim Minchin.

00:54:11.424 --> 00:54:13.340
I don't know how he came
up with these lyrics.

00:54:13.340 --> 00:54:15.820
But it's right on the money.

00:54:15.820 --> 00:54:20.264
And I'd like to sing that now.

00:54:20.264 --> 00:54:23.680
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:54:23.680 --> 00:54:25.480
